Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: Kenya Airways; Oceanic Bank of Nigeria

-- B y   C h r i s   K a y
-- 
2011-07-18T16:35:44Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-18/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-kenya-airways-oceanic-bank-of-nigeria.html
Kenya’s All-Share Index dropped 1.2
percent to 67.26 by the 3 p.m. close in Nairobi, the lowest
level since March 10.  Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index declined 0.4 percent to 2,053 by
the 1:30 p.m. close in  Port Louis , the lowest since May 5. The
Ghana Stock Exchange Composite Index snapped seven days of
declines, gaining 0.2 percent to 1,176.58 by the 3 p.m. close in
Accra. The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index weakened 0.5
percent to 23,713.47 by 2:30 p.m. in Lagos, according to data
compiled by Bloomberg.  Namibia ’s FTSE/ Namibia Overall Index (FTN098) 
slumped for the second consecutive trading day, falling 1.1
percent to 838.38 by the 4 p.m. close in Windhoek, the biggest
fall since June 23.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Kenya Airways Ltd. (KNAL)  , sub-Saharan Africa’s third-
biggest airline, rose 0.25 shilling, or 0.7 percent, to 34.50
shillings, the third day of advances, after increasing its
flight network in West Africa.        Oceanic Bank International Plc (OCEANIC)  , a Nigerian
lender bailed out by the central bank two years ago, jumped 6
kobo, or 5 percent, to 1.26 naira, the highest level since July
12, after Diamond Bank Plc’s Chief Financial Officer Abdulrahman
Yinusa said it was in “tentative” talks to acquire Oceanic.  Scangroup Ltd. (SCAN KN), East Africa’s biggest marketing
and advertising company, gained a second day, climbing 1
shilling, or 2 percent, to 51.5 shillings,  after a Business
Daily report that the company’s market share increased to 80
percent to 71 percent in September.  UT Bank Ltd. (UTB)  , a Ghanaian lender, gained 2 pesewas,
or 6.1 percent,oc to 35 pesewas, the highest close since June 2,
2010, on speculation that profit increased in the first half.  The share-price jump occured “in anticipation of good
earnings for the first half,” Randy Mensah, a stock trader at
Accra-based Databank Financial Services Ltd., said in a
telephone interview today. “We expect between 20 percent and 30
percent growth in UT Bank’s first half profit over the previous
year’s half.”  To contact the reporter on this story:
